 EL = 1/2 × L × I2 = 1/2 × 1 × 32 = 4.5μJ  EL_INITIAL = 1/2 × COUT × V2 = 1/2 × COUT × 1.22  EL_FINAL = 1/2 × COUT × (V + ΔVOUT)2          = 1/2 × COUT × (1.2 + 0.06)2  EL_FINAL = EL_INITIAL + EL            (18)   For example, if the acceptable transient to a 3A load  step is 5%, by inserting ΔVOUT = 0.05 × 1.2V = 0.06V  and ΔIOUT = 3.0A, the minimum required capacitance  will be 60.98μF. Generally, the ESR of ceramic  capacitors is small enough. The impact of output  capacitor ESR on the transient is not taken into account  in Equation 18.       2.9V to 6V Input, 6A Output,  SGM61060  Synchronous Buck Converter      22  JANUARY 2024  SG Micro Corp  www.sg-micro.com  APPLICATION INFORMATION (continued)  Equation 19 can be used for the output ripple criteria  and finding the needed minimum output capacitance.  VORIPPLE is the maximum acceptable ripple. In this  example, the allowed ripple is 30mV that results in  minimum capacitance of 16μF.  × × OUT ORIPPLE SW RIPPLE 1 1 C V 8 f I  >              (19)  where  • VRIPPLE is the maximum allowable output voltage  ripple.  • IRIPPLE is the inductor ripple current.  Note that the impact of output capacitor ESR on the  ripple is not considered in Equation 19. Use Equation  20 to calculate the maximum acceptable ESR of the  output capacitor to meet the output voltage ripple  requirement. In this example, the ESR must be less  than 30mV/1.92A = 15.6mΩ.  ORIPPLE ESR RIPPLE V R I <                  (20)  Higher nominal capacitance value must be chosen due  to aging, temperature, and DC bias derating of the  output capacitors. In this example, a 47μF/10V X5R  ceramic capacitor with 3mΩ of ESR is used. The  amount of ripple current that a capacitor can handle  without damage or overheating is limited. The inductor  ripple is bypassed through the output capacitor.  Equation 21 calculates the RMS current that the output  capacitor must support. In this example, it is 554.3mA.  OUT INMAX OUT CORMS INMAX 1 SW V (V V ) I 12 V L f × −